<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-income-tax-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Income Tax II</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Compute income tax using taxation table
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To discover the mechanism of a progressive tax structure, explore why tax burdens change across various income thresholds, and examine the purpose of post-tax relief mechanisms.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Organize learners into small collaborative task groups. Guide them to discuss and fill in the missing entries in the introductory <em>Income Level vs. Tax Effect</em> table. Circulate to ensure learners understand that under a progressive taxation model, higher incomes do not just pay more tax overall, but are subject to increasing marginal tax percentages. Prompt deep evaluation during the <em>Higher Order Thinking Task</em> regarding why personal relief is deducted from gross tax rather than being subtracted directly from gross earnings.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </axiom>
        <activity>
            <statement>

                <p>
                    <term>Work in Groups to:</term>
                </p>

                <p>
                    In real taxation systems, income is not taxed at a single rate. Instead, different portions of income are taxed at different rates. This system is called a <term>progressive tax system</term>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    In this activity, learners investigate how tax increases as income increases, and how personal relief affects final PAYE.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Identify how workers with different salaries contribute differently to taxation and discuss fairness in the tax system.
                </p>

                <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
                    <row header="yes">
                        <cell>Income Level</cell>
                        <cell>Possible Tax Effect</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Low income worker</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Middle income worker</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>High income worker</cell>
                        <cell>?</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>

                <p>
                    <alert>Case Study 1:</alert>
                </p>

                <p>
                    A worker earns a taxable income of Ksh <m>10,000</m>. The income falls within the tax band Ksh <m>1 - 12,298</m> which is taxed at <m>10\%</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <term>In groups</term>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>Calculate the gross tax payable.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Interpret what the tax percentage means in real life.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Case Study 2:</alert>
                </p>

                <p>
                    After computing tax, a worker finds that his gross tax is Ksh <m>4,500</m>. He is entitled to a personal relief of Ksh <m>2,400</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Determine his net tax (PAYE).
                </p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Higher Order Thinking Task:</alert>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Discuss:
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>Why does the government apply relief after tax is calculated and not before?</li>
                        <li>What happens to take-home pay when relief increases?</li>
                        <li>Why do higher income earners contribute more tax?</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

                <p>
                    <alert>Extension Challenge:</alert>
                </p>

                <p>
                    Suppose a worker earns a higher salary that falls into multiple tax bands. Discuss how tax is applied on different portions of income rather than the whole income at once.
                </p>

            </statement>
        </activity>

    

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize multi-tiered statutory slab partitions and anchor the operational sequence for calculating progressive PAYE balances.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Review the exploratory table from the anchor task. Explicitly demonstrate that in progressive systems, tax calculations do not apply a single high rate to an individual's entire salary pool. Instead, the total income is sectioned into separate layers or "slabs," and each layer is taxed at its own corresponding rate.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>The Mechanism of the "Excess" Band:</alert> Walk learners through what happens when an income overflows a given tax bracket. Show that you must tax the maximum width of the fully saturated lower slabs first, and then apply the subsequent higher percentage rate strictly to the remaining portion (the excess balance) that falls into the next band.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Consolidating Reductions and Reliefs:</alert> Standardize the terminal computation process on the chalkboard: <m>\text{Net PAYE}\; = \;\text{Sum of Bracket Taxes}\; - \;(\text{Personal Relief} \;+\; \text{Insurance Relief})</m>. Emphasize that net pay can then be determined by subtracting this final Net PAYE alongside any other non-tax deductions (such as SHA, WCPS, or SACCO loans) from the individual's original gross salary.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
"
    <insight>
        <p>
            Income tax is calculated using a progressive system where different portions of income are taxed at different rates depending on income level.
        </p>

        <p>
            The taxation process involves:
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Gross Tax} = \amp \; \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Applicable Rate(s)} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Net Tax (PAYE)} = \amp \; \text{Gross Tax} - \text{Personal Relief} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            In a progressive system, only portions of income fall into higher tax bands, meaning tax increases with income but not uniformly.
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>
                Tax systems are designed to distribute financial responsibility fairly, ensuring higher earners contribute more while relief protects low-income earners.
            </em>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr.Masimba earns a basic salary of sh. <m>15,000</m> per month. In addition, he gets a medical allowance of sh. <m>2,400</m>, and a house allowance of sh. <m>12,000</m>. Calculate the tax he pays in a year.
            </p>
            <tabular left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" top="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Income (K£ per annum)</cell>
                    <cell>Rate (Rate (sh. per pound))</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>1 - 5,808</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>5,809 - 11,280</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>11,281 - 16,752</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>16,753 - 22,224</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> Excess over <m>22,224</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                <alert>Relief</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Every employee in kenya is tittled to an automatic personal tax relief of sh. <m>12,672</m> p.a. (sh. <m>1056</m> per month).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            An employee with a life insurance policy on his life, that of his wife, or children may make a tax claim on the premium paid towards the policy at sh. <m>3</m> per pound subject to a maximum claim of sh. <m>3,000</m> per month.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Taxable income per month}\; =\amp \; \text{sh.}\;(15,000 + 2,400 + 12,000) </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =\; \text{sh.}\; 29,400</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Converting to K£ p.a.} \; \amp = \;\text{K£} \; 29,400 \times \frac{12}{20}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \;\text{K£}\; 17,640 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Tax due
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{First slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 5,808 \times 2 = \text{sh.}\; 11,616 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Second slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 5,472 \times 3 = \text{sh.}\; 16,416 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Third slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 5,472 \times 4 = \text{sh.}\; 21,888 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Foorth slab}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.} \; 888 \times 5 = \text{sh.}\; 4,440 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total tax due} \; \amp =\; \text{sh.} \;54,360</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Less personal relief} \; \amp = \;\text{sh.}\; 12,672 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Therefore, tax payable p.a.}\; \amp = \;\text{sh.}\; 41,688 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr Odhiambo is a senior teacher on a basic salary of Ksh. <m>16,000</m>. On top of his salary, he gets a house allowance of Ksh. <m>12,000</m>, a medical allowence of Ksh. <m>3,060</m>, and a hardship allowance of Ksh. <m>4,635</m>. He has a life insurance polivcy for which he pays Ksh. <m>800</m> per month and claims an insurance relief.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use the tax table below to calculate his PAYE.
                        </p>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                            <row header="yes">
                                <cell>Income in £ per month</cell>
                                <cell>Rate <m>(\%)</m> </cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1 - 484</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>10</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>485 - 940</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>15</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>941 - 1,396</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1,397 - 1,852</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>25</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>\text{Excess over}\; 1,852 </m></cell>
                                <cell><m>30</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            In addition to the PAYE, the following deductions are made on his pay everymonth:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="(i)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                       WCPS at <m>2 \%</m> of his basic salary.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        SHA Ksh. <m>400</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Co-operative shares on loan recovery Ksh. <m>4,800.</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Calculate his net pay.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            PAYE
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Taxable income}\; \amp = \; \text{Ksh.}\; (16,000 + 12,000 + 3,060 + 4,635) </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; 35,695 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Converting to K£} =\amp \; \text{K£}\; \frac{35,695}{20} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{K£}\; 1,784.75 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Gross tax
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\text{First slab} : \amp \;\text{K£}\; 484 \times \frac{10}{100} = \; \text{K£} \; 48.40 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Second slab} : \amp \;\text{K£}\; 456 \times \frac{15}{100} = \; \text{K£} \; 68.40 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Third slab} : \amp \;\text{K£}\; 456 \times \frac{20}{100} = \; \text{K£} \; 91.20 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Forth slab} : \amp \;\text{K£}\; 388 \times \frac{25}{100} = \; \text{K£} \; 97.00 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Gross tax} \; \amp = \; \text{K£}\; 305.00 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp =\; \text{Ksh.}\; 6,100 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                
                                <mrow> \text{Insurance relief} \; \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; \frac{800}{20} \times 3 = \text{Ksh.}\; 120 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Personal relief} \; \amp = \; \text{Ksh.}\; 1,056 </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Total relief} \; \amp = \; \text{Ksh.}\; 1,176 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Tax payable per month} \; \amp = \; \text{Gross tax} \;- \text{Total relief} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; (6,100 - 1,176) = \;\text{Ksh.}\; 4,924 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore PAYE is Ksh. <m>4,924</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Net pay
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Net pay} \; \amp = \; \text{Taxable income}\; - \; \text{Total deductions} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \text{Total deductions}\; \amp = \; \text{PAYE} \; + \; \text{Other deductions} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; (4,924 + \frac{2}{100} \times 16,000 + 400 + 4,800 + 800) </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; 11,244 </mrow>
                                <mrow>\text{Net pay}\; =  \amp \; \text{Ksh.}\; (35,695 - 11,244) </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \; \text{Ksh.} \; 24,451 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        
    </example>
            



